        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 68-year-old man from the Czech Republic who presents for oncology follow-up after a prior diagnosis of prostate cancer. He describes himself as feeling extremely good at present, with stable day-to-day functioning since surgery, and he is mainly concerned with understanding his diagnosis wording and keeping up with surveillance rather than with major current symptoms [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He is neatly dressed, calm, and attentive during the visit, speaking in a practical, informed way about his prior treatment and follow-up needs [MEDDIALOG:C61:0].\n\nHe lives a steady retired lifestyle and spends much of his week with his spouse, adult children, and a few close friends. He enjoys walks, light gardening, and watching football, and he tries to keep active without overexerting himself. He values routine and has become especially disciplined about medical appointments and laboratory monitoring after his cancer treatment [MEDDIALOG:C61:0].\n\n{patientName} says the cancer was originally diagnosed years ago and was described as very high grade, with a Gleason score of 10/10 [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He underwent radical prostatectomy and later received intermittent hormonal therapy with Lupron and Casodex, after which he continued to feel well overall [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He understands that prostate cancer and the phrase “malignant neoplasm of prostate” refer to the same condition, and he comes in wanting reassurance and clear guidance about ongoing PSA monitoring [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:bd7117f8-e4e3-47fa-9ca2-ca9b6170ea32",
