        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports that he was diagnosed with prostate cancer in 2006 and that pathology described a Gleason score of 10/10, consistent with high-risk disease [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He underwent radical prostatectomy the same year and was subsequently treated with intermittent Lupron and Casodex through oncology follow-up [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He states that his overall condition has been extremely good since surgery [MEDDIALOG:C61:0].\n\nHe presents now for routine reassessment and clarification of terminology seen on prior records, specifically the phrase “malignant neoplasm of prostate,” which he learned is simply another term for prostate cancer [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He understands the need for regular PSA surveillance after prostatectomy, including attention to whether PSA rises above 0.2 ng/mL and whether it ever reached below 0.03 ng/mL after treatment, both of which carry prognostic significance [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He denies any major interval decline in function and remains engaged with follow-up care [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]."
          }
        ]
      }
